[2] Maine (Hancock, York, Waldo counties)
Date: Fri 15 Feb 2019 1:00 AM EST
Source: Bangor Daily News (BDN) [edited]
https://bangordailynews.com/2019/02/15/news/hancock/whooping-cough-cases-on-the-rise-in-maine-with-nearly-30-percent-in-hancock-county/


Reported cases of whooping cough spiked in Maine last month [January 2019] to more than twice what that had been the prior year [2018], according to the state's public health agency. Overall, Maine had 55 reported cases of pertussis last month, up from 24 in January 2018, according to the Maine Center of Disease Control and Prevention's latest disease surveillance report released earlier this week [week of 4 Feb 2019].

Of the 55 cases, 39 were in just 3 of Maine's 16 counties. Hancock county had the most with 16, York county had 13, and Waldo county had 10. More than half the cases affected children and teenagers between 11 and 19 years old, according to the Maine CDC.

The CDC last month [January 2019] declared only one outbreak of pertussis at an unidentified K-12 school in York county. Of nearly 450 reported cases of pertussis in Maine in 2018, York county had the most, with 174 reported cases. 20 outbreaks were identified in Maine last year [2018], with 9 occurring in York county and 4 in Hancock county.

In Hancock county, concern about the spread of pertussis last month [January 2019] prompted school officials with Regional School Unit [RSU] 24, which serves 9 towns, and at Ellsworth Elementary Middle School to send out notifications to parents. One case was confirmed at the Ellsworth school, but information about whether any cases were confirmed at RSU 24 schools was not made public. According to a report in the Ellsworth American weekly newspaper, 11 cases of whooping cough were reported at George Stevens Academy in Blue Hill between early November [2018] and mid-January [2019].

[Byline: Bill Trotter]

