[3] South Dakota (Sioux Falls)
Date: Thu 21 Feb 2019 4:43 PM EST
Source: Argus Leader [abridged, edited]
https://eu.argusleader.com/story/news/education/2019/02/21/pertussis-south-dakota-school-district-whooping-cough-symptoms-vaccinations/2937752002/


Pertussis cases are increasing in South Dakota, with the state already seeing 27 cases early in 2019. In particular, the Sioux Falls School District has seen 10 cases in 11 different schools since December [2018].

We spoke with Dr Joshua Clayton, the state epidemiologist for the South Dakota Department of Health, to find out what you need to know. Nationwide, there are between 10 000 and 40 000 cases of pertussis per year on average. Out of the 27 cases in South Dakota so far in 2019, 18 of them have been in children under 5 years old, Clayton said.

Why is South Dakota seeing more pertussis cases? Pertussis outbreaks tend to be cyclical, with spikes occurring every 3 to 5 years in general, Clayton said. In 2014, there were 109 cases, but that number dropped to as low as 9 in 2017 before skyrocketing to 162 cases in 2018. "Every 3 to 5 years we do see an increase," Clayton said. "Part of that is due to waning immunity." Unlike some vaccines, pertussis vaccines are only 85 percent effective, Clayton said, meaning there is a chance people who have been vaccinated will still get sick. Immunity typically only lasts about 2 years before beginning to decline.

Molly Satter, the health services coordinator for the Sioux Falls School District, said 9 out of the 10 cases seen in the district this winter [2018-19] were up to date on their shots. Of the more than 23 000 students enrolled in the district, upward of 98 percent are fully vaccinated, she said.

In addition, the CDC says getting the pertussis vaccine can help prevent infection and lessen the severity of symptoms, even if you do get the disease. Before the pertussis vaccine was introduced in the 1940s, about 200 000 children contracted pertussis and 9000 died each year from it. Now, out of the 10 000 to 40 000 cases seen nationwide each year (https://www.cdc.gov/pertussis/images/incidence-graph-2017.jpg), only 20 people die each year.

[Byline: Katie Nelson]

