[6] Tasmania
Date: Wed 20 Feb 2019 10:30 AM AEDT
Source: The Advocate [edited]
https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/5914371/whooping-cough-reported-at-north-west-school/


A North-West primary school has reported a case of whooping cough. Somerset Primary will send a note with more information home with the oldest child in each family on [Tue 19 Feb 2019].

Statistics from Communicable Diseases Prevention Clinical Director Dr Faline Howes suggest that Tasmania is in the midst of an outbreak. There have been 124 notifications of whooping cough in January this year [2019]. This is an increase from 103 in December 2018, and 84 in November.

Dr Howes said Tasmanian outbreaks usually last for months and involve people of all ages over the whole state, with babies under 6 months of age being most at risk of life-threatening diseases. Whooping cough, also known as pertussis, is an infection caused by bacteria that affects the lungs and airways.

Last year [2018] there was an outbreak of the disease on the coast prompting a warning for people to check their vaccinations were up to date.

[Byline: Meg Powell]

